<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-492-040  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 492 040.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Macworld  July 1990 v7 n7 p136(9).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The magnetic-field menace. (health hazards from computerterminals)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brodeur, Paul.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Research suggests that exposure to electromagnetic emissions fromcomputer monitors may have harmful health effects, butmanufacturers and employers continue to cloud the issue by denyingthe hazard and government regulatory agencies handle itincompetently.andP;  Computer monitors emit very low frequency (VLF)and extremely low frequency (ELF) magnetic fields, which have beenlinked to high incidences of leukemia and brain tumors amongelectricians, power-line workers, and telephone workers.andP;  Manystudies in medical literature suggest that alternating currentfields may cause cancer, possibly by weakening the body's immunesystem.andP;  Weak ELF fields have been found to alter brain chemistryin laboratory animals and interfere with the ability ofT-lymphocyte cells to kill cancer cells.andP;  New evidence links VDTuse to miscarriages and birth defects among women who work withcomputers.andP;  Apple has given equivocal responses to usersexpressing concern, forcing computer users to decide forthemselves whether manufacturers are dealing forthrightly with theproblem.andP;  Vendors' rationale is that there is 'no conclusiveproof,' but the fact that scientists do not understand themechanism by which monitors cause cancer does not mean that thereis no effect.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersMonitorsHealth.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographgraph.andO;Caption:   Electromagnetic spectrum. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>